Before I start digging into 39 pages of glory, what are people&#39;s ideas
for phenotypic morphologies? I was feeling all inspired that this was
the next big thing, and I go to send the group an e-mail about it, and
instead I read five different posts getting into the philosophy of it
all. I love it.

Looking at the &#39;standard&#39; genotype, there is two sets of numbers, one
for the activation of the neurons, with one for each neuron, then a
second list of numbers, with the weights, sources, and destinations of
the links.

I am playing around with an additional history integration paramter,
that effects the neurons, but the idea is the same. We are inheriting
the graph structure idea from computer science classes with nodes and
edges, and making brains out of them.

Now we want to evolve the structure by having part of our genome
describe the expression of the genome into a phenotype. Ideas that come
to mind are to embed our current idea of genotype into a larger genotype
idea. In this super genome, a &quot;gene&quot; referes to what we have been
calling a &#39;network.&#39; This network evolves using the same NEAT we&#39;ve been
playing with. In the super NEAT genome, each network is treated in the
same way as neuron is treated. Some changes in the super NEAT might
include mutating the number of inputs and outputs a network gene has (
slowly enough for the network to work with the new topology ).
This approach doesn&#39;t seem to me to be the best way to encorage profound
symetries that drasticly reduce search space, but it still might work,
and be a start.

I just felt like I had to get that out there before I started reading
that paper. 39 pages. Wow. These things don&#39;t read like pulp fiction.

chad

